Exercise 5

What function from the tidyverse do we use the add a new variable to a data frame while keeping the existing variables?

The â€˜mutateâ€™ function.

The following function is provided by Data Science in a box and is calculating the distance between two locations (lat, long).

haversine <- function(long1, lat1, long2, lat2, round = 3) {
  # convert to radians
  long1 = long1 * pi / 180
  lat1  = lat1  * pi / 180
  long2 = long2 * pi / 180
  lat2  = lat2  * pi / 180
  
  R = 6371 # Earth mean radius in km
  
  a = sin((lat2 - lat1)/2)^2 + cos(lat1) * cos(lat2) * sin((long2 - long1)/2)^2
  d = R * 2 * asin(sqrt(a))
  
  return( round(d,round) ) # distance in km
}

Exercise 6

Calculate the distances between all pairs of Dennyâ€™s and La Quinta locations and save this variable as distance. Make sure to save this variable in THE dn_lq_ak data frame so that you can use it later.

dn_lq_ak <- dn_lq_ak %>%
  mutate(distance = haversine(longitude.x, latitude.x, longitude.y, latitude.y))
dn_lq_ak

Exercise 7

Calculate the minimum distance between a Dennyâ€™s and La Quinta for each Dennyâ€™s location. To do so we group by Dennyâ€™s locations and calculate a new variable that stores the information for the minimum distance.

dn_lq_ak_mindist <- dn_lq_ak %>%
  group_by(address.x) %>%
  summarise(closest = min(distance))
dn_lq_ak_mindist

Exercise 8

Describe the distribution of the distances Dennyâ€™s and the nearest La Quinta locations in Alaska. Also include an appripriate visualization and relevant summary statistics.

Exercise 12

Among the states you examined, where is Mitch Hedbergâ€™s joke most likely to hold true? Explain your reasoning.

Most likely the joke holds in Alaska, North Carolina, and Texas. The distribution of the closest distance are in these areas around 5 km (median) which could be defined as â€˜closeâ€™. Texas should be mentioned, that the distribution is very broad and therefore not meaningful for this study (Not every La Quinta location is close to a Dennyâ€™s).

Besides, New York as self-defined state in the U.S. does not hold the joke, because the median distance between both Dennyâ€™s and La Quinta is 25 km, which is not close compared to the other states.

Function - Create dataframe by state

  1. Get all of lab 5 working, to include creating a function that takes a â€œstateâ€ as input and produces the output dataframe of distinces.
  2. Modify (probably already done in class) so that â€¦ given a state, if creates a dataframe that for each la quinta, it includes distance to nearest dennys.
analyze_state <- function(this_state) {
  
  dn_state <- dn %>%
    filter(state == this_state)
  
  lq_state <- lq %>%
    filter(state == this_state)
  
  dm_lq_state_mindist <-- full_join(dn_state, lq_state, by = "state") %>%
    mutate(
      distance = haversine(longitude.x, latitude.x, longitude.y, latitude.y, round = 4)
    ) %>%
    group_by(address.x) %>%
    summarise(closest = min(distance))
  
  return( dm_lq_state_mindist )
}

  1. Create a function that takes a â€œstateâ€ as input and produces a dataframe, where there is one observation per â€œla quintaâ€ and it lists distance to nearest â€œRestaurantâ€. WHEN YOU BUILD THIS FUNCTION â€¦ ensure it is pulling a sample from the state of interest AND that the sample size is similar to the number of Dennyâ€™s in the state. (Hint - use â€œsample_nâ€ function from dplyr.)
test <- function(this_state, this_restaurant) {
  
  dn_state <- dn %>%
    filter(state == this_state)
  
  lq_state <- lq %>%
    filter(state == this_state)
  
  fastfood_state <- FastFoodRestaurants %>%
    filter(state == this_state) %>%
    filter(name == this_restaurant)
  
  fastfood_sample <- sample_n(fastfood_state, nrow(dn_state))
  
  dn_mindist <- full_join(dn_state, lq_state, by = "state") %>%
    mutate(
      distance = haversine(longitude.x, latitude.x, longitude.y, latitude.y, round = 4)
    ) %>%
    group_by(address.x) %>%
    summarise(closest = min(distance)) %>%
    mutate(name = "dennys")

  ff_mindist <- full_join(fastfood_sample, lq_state, by = "state") %>%
    mutate(
      distance = haversine(longitude.x, latitude.x, longitude.y, latitude.y, round = 4)
    ) %>%
    group_by(address.x) %>%
    summarise(closest = min(distance)) %>%
    mutate(name = this_restaurant)
  
  
  
  return (ff_mindist)
}
test_df <- test("NY", "mcdonalds")
